      "source": [
        "## Summary:\n",
        "\n",
        "### Data Analysis Key Findings\n",
        "\n",
        "*   The `transformers` library was confirmed to be pre-installed, and a `bert-base-uncased` model and tokenizer were successfully loaded.\n",
        "*   BERT embeddings were generated for 1490 articles, resulting in a new feature set of dimension `(1490, 768)`, which was added to the DataFrame.\n",
        "*   These BERT embeddings were successfully combined with existing features (`combined_scaled_features`), creating a `final_combined_features` matrix with a shape of `(1490, 5778)`.\n",
        "*   Contrary to expectations, the `RandomForestClassifier` trained with the combined features including BERT embeddings showed a significant performance degradation, achieving an overall accuracy of 0.91 and a macro average F1-score of 0.90. This is lower than the previous models (0.95 accuracy with n-grams only, and 0.94 accuracy with n-grams + lexicon/NER/sentiment).\n",
        "*   The 'tech' category, a primary focus for improvement, experienced the most severe negative impact, with its F1-score dropping from 0.94 (n-grams only) to 0.85 (with BERT embeddings). Its recall decreased notably to 0.79, indicating that 11 out of 52 actual 'tech' articles in the test set were misclassified.\n",
        "*   Most other categories ('business', 'entertainment', 'politics') also experienced F1-score decreases (from 0.92 to 0.88 for business, 0.97 to 0.92 for entertainment, and 0.93 to 0.91 for politics).\n",
        "*   The 'sport' category maintained strong performance across all models, achieving a consistent F1-score of 0.97.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Insights or Next Steps\n",
        "\n",
        "*   The direct concatenation of high-dimensional BERT embeddings with existing features and subsequent use with a `RandomForestClassifier` did not improve classification performance and instead led to degradation. This suggests that the current integration method may introduce too much noise or redundancy, or that `RandomForestClassifier` is not optimally suited for dense contextual embeddings.\n",
        "*   Future efforts should focus on investigating alternative integration strategies, such as dimensionality reduction (e.g., PCA, UMAP) on the BERT embeddings, exploring different machine learning models better suited for high-dimensional and dense features (e.g., SVMs, Gradient Boosting Machines, or neural networks), or considering fine-tuning a BERT model directly on the classification task.\n"
      ]
    },
